03975nam a22005655i 9780822381655DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t19921992ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1226678561  a97808223816557 a10.1515/97808223816552doi  a(DE-B1597)553825  a(OCoLC)1136200528  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBX4946.M3bB69 1991 7aBIO0000002bisacsh1 aBoyd, Stephen B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPilgram Marpeck :bHis Life and Social Theology /cStephen B. Boyd. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (212 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDuke Monographs in Medieval and Renaissance Studies : 49 ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tIntroduction -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter 1 Rattenberg: crisis of loyalty -- tChapter 2 the »mystery of the cross«: theologies of suffering -- tChapter 3 Strassburg: social and religious radicalism -- tChapter 4 Marpeck's theology of the cross and the christian community -- tChapter 5 Interim Years: struggle for unity and institutional identity -- tChapter 6 Augsburg: confessional pluralism and political conflict -- tChapter 7 Gerechtigkeit and Marpeck's social theology -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis intellectual and social history is the first comprehensive biography of Pilgram Marpeck (c. 1495-1556), a radical reformer and lay leader of Anabaptist groups in Switzerland, Austria, and South Germany. Marpeck's influential life and work provide a glimpse of the theologies and practices of the Roman Church and of various reform movements in sixteenth-century Europe.Drawing on extensive archival data documenting Marpeck's professional life, as well as on his numerous published and unpublished writings on theology and religious reform, Stephen B. Boyd traces Marpeck's unconventional transition from mining magistrate to Anabaptist leader, establishes his connections with various radical social and religious groups, and articulates aspects of his social theology. Marpeck's distinctive and eclectic theology, Boyd demonstrates, focused on the need for personal, uncoerced conversion, rejected state interference in the affairs of the church, denied the need for a monastic withdrawal from the secular world, and called for the Christian's active pursuit of justice before God and among human beings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAnabaptistsvBiography. 0aAnabaptistsxDoctrinesxHistoryy16th century. 0aChristian sociologyxHistoryy16th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822381655zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822381655423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822381655/original  a978-3-11-071360-2  Duke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles